{"id":"2211.10034","submitter":"Saugata Basu","authors":"Saugata Basu and Ali Mohammad-Nezhad","title":"Improved effective {\\L}ojasiewicz inequality and applications","comments":"29 pages. Theorem 1 expanded to include a bound on the constant $c$\n  in the integer case. Comments welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.LO math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $\\mathrm{R}$ be a real closed field. Given a closed and bounded\nsemi-algebraic set $A \\subset \\mathrm{R}^n$ and semi-algebraic continuous\nfunctions $f,g:A \\rightarrow \\mathrm{R}$, such that $f^{-1}(0) \\subset\ng^{-1}(0)$, there exist $N$ and $c \\in \\mathrm{R}$, such that the inequality\n({\\L}ojasiewicz inequality) $|g(x)|^N \\le c \\cdot |f(x)|$ holds for all $x \\in\nA$. In this paper we consider the case when $A$ is defined by a quantifier-free\nformula with atoms of the form $P = 0, P >0, P \\in \\mathcal{P}$ for some finite\nsubset of polynomials $\\mathcal{P} \\subset \\mathrm{R}[X_1,\\ldots,X_n]_{\\leq\nd}$, and the graphs of $f,g$ are also defined by quantifier-free formulas with\natoms of the form $Q = 0, Q >0, Q \\in \\mathcal{Q}$, for some finite set\n$\\mathcal{Q} \\subset \\mathrm{R}[X_1,\\ldots,X_n,Y]_{\\leq d}$. We prove that the\n{\\L}ojasiewicz exponent $N$ in this case is bounded by $(8 d)^{2(n+7)}$. Our\nbound depends on $d$ and $n$, but is independent of the combinatorial\nparameters, namely the cardinalities of $\\mathcal{P}$ and $\\mathcal{Q}$. As a\nconsequence we improve the current best error bounds for polynomial systems\nunder some conditions. Finally, as an abstraction of the notion of independence\nof the {\\L}ojasiewicz exponent from the combinatorial parameters occurring in\nthe descriptions of the given pair of functions, we prove a version of\n{\\L}ojasiewicz inequality in polynomially bounded o-minimal structures. We\nprove the existence of a common {\\L}ojasiewicz exponent for certain\ncombinatorially defined infinite (but not necessarily definable) families of\npairs of functions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Nov 2022 05:22:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Dec 2022 21:31:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-05"}
